review_blob: Yeasty aroma, coriander. Lemonady color to a deep orange. Medium body. Crisp carbonation. Orange and lemony flavor on the end. Alcohol on the end as well. Yeast flavors which I dont normally like but its not overdone. I really like the mix of flavors. Good job DFH.

Deep orange pour, not much of a head. Relatively thick mouthfeel. Nice on the tongue. Taste is mainly of hops (citrus). Long bitter aftertaste. Hops dont overwhelm which is nice. Light carbonation. I wish I could get more of an aroma except I just took a shower. Will have to rerate at another point but from what I can tell, very good beer. Would be a good beer with a variety of foo.
Dry  aroma, not much on the nose. Thick head for a stout. Pours black. Kind of watery. Wet finish. Long mocha finish.

Red/black color. Aroma is of dark fruits and chocolate. Thin body. Taste is interesting- dark chocolate (reminds me of hershey chocolate actually) with wine like flavors(?). Pleasant carbonation. Dry but a long finish.

Slighty hazy, deep golden color. Malts and hop aroma. Cleansing carbonation, followed by slight bitterness and then a long hop bitterness and a long finish. Really good refreshing beer that has deeper flavor than I wouldve originally thought.
Light brown color. Thin head. Nut, roasted aromas. Dry finish. Surprising bitterness on the back end. Wears down over the course of a pint.
Finally had this beer. Light orange color, frothy pour. Malty aroma. Spicy (pear?) aroma? Thin body. Malty taste. Not much carbonation, long finish.

Dark, dark brown pour, White, medium, head. Aroma is a light vanilla (theres a surprise). Thin to medium body, pleasant carbonation, not much bitterness at all. The bitterness that is there feels malt related(?) and is at the end. Vanilla, again, dominates throughout.

This was the first beer I had after finding out my first duty assignment. I decided to come to my favorite bar and have one beer, even though I had PT the next day. I considered long and hard and eventually decided upon a beer that honored my mother who opposed my decision to join the US Army- a Kalamazoo Stout. Kalamazoo Stout because Kalamazoo is where she went to university.

Pours black with a rather thick head for a stout, medium brown head. Aroma is of chocolate, molasses, and alcohol. Body is thin with some nice carbonation. Pleasant and smooth on the tongue, it really dances on the back corners. Taste is fruit then coffee on the back end with alcohol.

Pours dark brown. Think, dark brown head. Aroma is of molasses. The body is pretty thick. Tastes sugary, vanilla, bourbon and hints of chocolate at the end. Would not be surprised if this thing is a lot better after a few years.

Ok, just not my cup of tea. I just dont like the yeasty flavor. Pours gold orange color. Smells of cough syrup for some reason (I think its the alcohol). Taste is fruity, orangey. Medium body, pretty fat. Too big onthe booze I think.

Thick, dark pour. Slightly mahogany color. Relatively thick head for a porter (maybe it was just my pour though). Chocolate/peanut butter aroma. Thin on the tongue. Slightly burnt taste with dark chocolate on the end. No carbonation, not crisp, watery. Long, slightly bitter finish.
Light orange to dark color. Almost like apple cider. Medium thin head. Fruity aroma. Thick mouthfeel, very crisp. Slight bitterness at the end. Interesting beer.

Aroma of apples. Red brown color. Strange combination that it feels like I count wrap my mouth around it but its thin. Citrussy taste with carbonation dancing on your tongue. Hops at the end. Wet, long finish.

This is really an outstanding beer. Pours a light orange color with a thin head. Citrus and grapefruit on the nose. Palate is thick and fullbodied. Initial light, pleasant carbonation followed by bitterness and then sweet at the end. Long but crisp finish.

Aroma is that of dark fruits and chocolate. When you taste it, the medium body is immediately evident followed by some crisp carbonation which is nice, bitterness and then dark chocolate. Long finish. Very good beer from DFH!
Pours a thin head. Hoppy aroma. Taste is bitterness then carbonation with a more bitter aftertaste. Theres also a light sweetness to it. The beer is quite cleansing.

This is a decent but not great IPA. It hits everything you want of an IPA but theres no oomph to it that would bring it to greatness. But to its credit, it takes all the classic parts of the IPA and balances them well and some might argue that is harder to do than the oomph IPAs. 

First, floral hops. Spicy too. And hints of pine. Pours a pretty thick head. Medium thinness in the body. Sweet initial taste and then aftertaste of hop bitterness. Crisp with definite carbonation. Again, not bad.
Aroma is tropical fruits. Pours really thick. Definitely notice aromatic hops in the aroma and the taste. Bunch of bitterness at the end.

Pours a thick, coal black. Brown tan head. Aroma is of banana and clove- the kind of notes youd think youd be getting from a Belgian ale. Chocolate is in there also. Tasting it is very interesting. First of all, the carbonation is a sparkly lightness that dances across your tongue. Its very fruity. Bitterness taps on the tip of your tongue and chocolate gradually eases its way onto the back. Its very smooth and silky. What an interesting beer.

Pours black with a dark tan head; medium size for the style. Initial aroma is soysauce. That leads to one of those what the f--k moments. Then I get the coffee in the aroma. The taste is nice, very crisp finish. The aftertaste is long lasting with hints of chocolate, roasted malts and expresso, especially at the end. First beer Ive had from this brewery and its a solid performance.

Pours a good head, slightly tan. Dark brown color almost like crayon brown, getting lighter as you move up the glass. Aroma is very complex. A lot of maltiness is the first impression with cinnamon or brown sugar notes. Nutty. Full body but thin. Bit watery, actually. Dry finish, kind of disappears in your mouth. Some bitterness in the aftertaste but also a fair bit of chocolate, I want to say. This is a very complex, very deep beer but then, perhaps Im judging it just because its better than Newcastle which Ive had a lot. Im not typically a fan of browns but this is definitely worth paying for it. Glad I bought a pony keg of it!
Soft taste. Malty with hints of bitterness. Has kind of a coca-colaish feel to it. Floral aroma. Bit of a sweet aroma.

Appearance is orange, slightly brown. Aroma is citrussy with hints of pine. When you sip it, you definitely feel a cleansing carbonation and with the bitterness of the hops would make a very good pairing with some spicy food. Thin body. The finish is interesting- it felt long lasting but then had a real quick, crisp finish. Dont think Ive ever encountered that before.

Pours black with a small white head. Very soft milk aroma, hints of milk chocolate. The beer is really thick. Theres a definite milk chocolate taste to it, just like in its aroma. Definitite taste of alcohol. The bitterness sits on the back of your tongue. Its almost like a candy bar. I got a hint of floralness too in the taste but that mightve been because I was drunk at the time.

A very interesting beer. The first thing you notice with the aroma is definitely the bitter coffee. Very strong aroma. Tasting it is a revelation, namely because it is initially bitter but its not the bitterness of chocolate but the bitterness of hops youd normally associate with a pale ale, then it morphs into coffee with undernotes of chocolate and alcohol with a relatively dry finish. Its a bit thin which I actually appreciated from a coffee like stout as this. Given the hop character of this beer, I liked it.

Pours a golden hazy color with a medium head. Aroma is of floral hops- that of a classic pale ale. Theres soem carbonation then a crisp but lingering finish. I really like the initial carbonation. It wipes your palate. Solid pale ale.
The aroma is very bready with banana. It pours a yeasty, orange brown color. Tastes a lot like a hefeweizen but a bit thicker. Long finish.

Slightly cloudy golden color. The aroma is of grass and straw, dont quite know what else. Its a bit sweet with good carbonation and a crisp finish that before it disappears, sits in the back of the mouth. This would be a good summer beer. Theres something in the beer thats just a bit offputting though, dunno what.

Pours a thick, almost charcoal black with a thin head. The aroma is chocolately and burnt fruit. When I had it, the first thing I noticed taste wise was that it seemed fruity with some raisins. The body is pretty thin. I realize this scores quite high but I am not a fan of the style.

Pours really syrupy, with an orange brown color. Aroma is of hops and barleywine (not sophisticated enough with this style to pick out the notes). First taste is quite bitter and then turns to sweetness with a long finish. To be honest, I havent had enough barleywines to distinguish how this is better than the rest that Ive tried.

Aroma is of mild hops, cranberries. Pours a small head with a coca-colaish color. The first thing you notice is it the bubbles with the carbonation, then the hint of malt finishing sour and with berry. It has a slightly puckering taste. I really want to get into sours but its just not my kidn of beer, unfortunately but this is a good turn for the style.

This was a real good beer. Like most stouts, its got little to no head; slightly offbrown. The color of the beer itself is a deep, almost black brown. Aroma is complex. After drinking it for a bit (maybe it was the pint glass), the biggest thing I got was a definite dark to even milk chocolate aroma and this was reflected in the taste. It was bitter but not the hoppy bitterness but rather, the more typical chocolate/coffee bitter. It tasted of chocolate, coffee and I want to say burnt fruit and molasses(?). Relatively dry finish. For a beer that is 11 percent alcohol, I didnt taste a lot of the booze and it didnt warm my stomach to a noticeable degree. Very solid stout.
beer_name: Laughing Dog The Dogfather Imperial Stout

review_blob: Good beer. I had it at the Green Leafe, here in Williamsburg, during Trivia Night. Maybe the atmosphere got in the way of me getting a lot of flavor out of the beer. I found that the aroma was one of floral, light hops. It pours a copper gold. Good beer to look at. The taste? Slightly sweet and decently bitter (not a huge hop bomb). The beer lingers. Its got a nice long finish, not dry at all. Theres a pleasant carbonation to it that I thing makes the sweetness seem not too offensive. Its nothing outstanding but then, this isnt my style. But its a very drinkable beer (I dont mean that condescendingly either) and its something Id gladly keep in my fridge.

This was an interesting beer. I had it on tap at the Green Leafe. Maybe Ive not had that many winter ales but this almost tasted like a bit of a sweeter IPA. The aroma was citrus, pine and some fruit. It was a pretty full flavor with a solid body but the finish was a bit wetter and longer than I like. My only complaint is that it seemed to progressively get worse as I was drinking it but I think that is reflective of the body of the beer. Decent beer if you only have a pint of it.
beer_name: Southern Tier Old Man Winter Ale

review_blob: When they say coffee stout, boy are they not kidding. I caught a whiff of this thing from practically three feet away. Its a decent beer. It was on tap and in a mug (Green Leafe mug night) so I didnt see the pour or the appearance. It looked like little to no head. The first thing you notice is obviously the coffee. I didnt get any other aromas. The taste is not that bad. It overpowers you with the coffee but interestingly enough, theres a bit of an chocolate on the underside (I guess not surprising). Its a bit thin, for my tastes and Ive definitely had better stouts. Still, not a bad brew from Williamsburg Alewerks.

Soft, bready aroma. Decent amount of flavor but nothing I could put my finger on. Incredibly light. Disappointing for a kolsch. Maybe Im not sophisticated enough to get the bouquet of flavors or maybe they just arent there.

Pretty decent aroma of hops and grass. Really flat taste- maybe that was just the pour. Theres something at the back of my sip that I cant quite get at. Hints of hops and spice and bread. Not much doing.
Pours pretty thick, billowy head. A soft aroma. Couldnt get much out of it. Thicker on the tongue, not much flavor. Nothing special.

Grassy aroma with some hops. Pours a thick head. It tastes a bit thin initially but proceeds to finish with a bit of spice and (to me) a lot of bread notes. This is your typical, middle of the road pilsener that I wouldnt mind drinking at a run of the mill restaurant or picking some up at the street corner.

Bottle from the store across the Ettaler monastery. Pours a dark amber. Mild head. Malty, deep flavor. Aroma is of hops, toffee. Hints of chocolate, bitterness at the end.  Thin body. Dry finish. Warms the stomach.

Pours thick charcoal. I put my nose to it and my first impression was cherry, which surprised me because its something Ive not ever tasted in a beer. Tasting it is wonderfully complex- you think its done but its not. Spice, chocolate, alcohol, a smooth taste. Theres something astringent at the end so I cant quite bring myself to like. Perhaps even too bitter at the end.
Difficult to figure out aroma. Hint of chocolate and maybe soy sauce(?). Typical black appearance with a rich, thick white head. Medium body. Definite chocolate in flavor.

Floral and pine on aroma. Pours a bit thick. Pretty hefty, frothy head. Deep orange/red color. Taste is quite something- complex, raisins, a bit of chocolate(?)(or am I confusing it with something else?) spicy. Aftertaste lingers and is of bitterness.

Deep red, small medium head. Almost smells like a wine. Tart and lasting sour taste at the end. Its got a deeper flavor than most krieks/lambics Ive had. Tastes of alcohol at the end. Thin mouthfeel. Not too much carbonation
Fruity aroma, with a hint of bubblegum. Deep, orange gold color. The mouthfeel is a bit thin. Citrus and notes of something I cant place. Its okay and a good value.
beer_name: Heavy Seas Red Sky At Night

review_blob: Thick, dark appearance. Hints of chocolate and barley in the nose. Thinner than appearance would suggest. Definitely got chocolate. Very good brown ale.

Appearance is golden and hazy. Pours with a thick head that stuck to the glass. Fruity, banana(?) aroma. Flavor is one of fruit, spice and hops with an aftertaste of alcohol. Good beer but just not to my liking.

On tap at PF Changs. Decent but light headed. Vivid golden color. Aroma is some malt but nothing distinguishable. Flavor is a bit sweet, bitter aftertaste (for an intl style pilsener), quite crisp but a bit thin. Nothing to write home about but a decent pilsener.
